#Abstract
#Drought has been identified as a dominant threat to the peanut industry. As the severity and duration of droughts are expected to increase
#alongside rapidly changing environmental conditions, new strategies are being developed to increase crop resilience to drought and other abiotic
#stressors. The host-associated microbiome acts as an extended layer of plant immunity by providing tolerance towards biotic and abiotic stressors,
#which has led to interest in how host-associated microbiome might be shaped by drought tolerant peanut cultivars to provide unique traits of 
#improved plant growth and stress resistance. To study potential baseline patterns of microbiome assembly across resistant cultivars of differing 
#drought tolerance mechanisms, we assessed microbial DNA samples from bulk soil, rhizosphere, and root endosphere compartments of six control group 
#peanut cultivars with unique physiological mechanisms of water tolerance (water-saver, water-spender, and sensitive host phenotypes) from Auburn
#University’s peanut breeding program. Results showed that, when grouped by phenotype, alpha diversity of bacterial and fungal communities had 
#highest differences among the bulk soil compartments. Significant changes in fungal diversity among host phenotype categories were observed among 
#the rhizosphere and root endosphere compartments, with uniquely enriched fungal genera seen in water spender and water saver phenotype in bulk 
#soil. This relationship between bacterial and fungal assembly patterns suggests a potential host-specific rhizosphere effect that could be 
#influenced by changes in root exudate composition or abiotic soil conditions associated with the host. Further work is needed to determine if 
#there is a link between microbial enrichment patterns and the physiological expression of drought tolerance among the three categories, or if 
#these associations directly contribute to the host’s ability to mount an effective defense response against drought stress.

